# Files
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What is file? 
Files are name location on disk to store information
They are used to store data permanently
Data is stored in non-volatile memory
We can retrive data whenever required.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Types of Files?
Text Files : Stores data in the form of Characters. It is used to store data and strings.
eg: .txt, .docx, .log etc.

Binary Files : Stores data in the form of bytes (group of 8-bits).
eg: .mp4, .mov, .png, .jpeg etc.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What is File Handling?
File Handling Means:-
- Opening a file
- Performing some Operations on it
- Closing a file.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Opening a File
Python provides a build-in function open() to open a file.

Syntax: f = open(filename, mode='r',)

filename :- file to be accessed

mode :- access mode (purpose of opening file.)
(if mode not specified it opens file in read mode)

f :- file handler, file pointer
(f points at start of the file)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Different Types of Modes:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Character              Meaning                                                     |
'r'            open for reading (default)                                          |
'r+'           open for reading and writing (no truncate),it overwrite from start  |
'w'            open for writing, truncating the file first                         |
'w+'           open for reading and writing (truncate and write)                   |
'x'            create a new file and open it for writing                           |
'a'            open for writing, appending to the end of the file if it exists     |
'a+'           open for reading and writing (appends to the end)                   |
'b'            binary mode                                                         |
't'            text mode (default)                                                 |
'+'            open a disk file for updating (reading and writing)                 |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Reading a File

data = f.read()            <- reads the entire file
date = f.readline()        <- reads one line at a time 

eg. for reading line one at a time 
f = open("demo.txt","r")
line1 = f.readline()        <- reads first line
print(line1)
f.close()
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Writing a File
Writing a file refers to process of transferring data from a programer's memory to a persistence storage location,
typically a file on a computer's file system.
This allows data to be saved and accessed even after program terminates.

f = open("demo.txt","w")           <- write mode
f.write("This is a new line")      <- overwrites the entire file

f = open("demo.txt","a")           <- append mode
f.write("This is a new line")      <- adds to the file
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
with Syntax

with open("demo.txt","r") as f:
      data = f.read()
      print(data)

with automatically closes the file 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Deleting a file 

using the os module
Module is a file written by another programmer that generally has a function we can use.

import os
os.remove(filename)

eg. 
import os 
os.remove("demo.txt")
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
